item.title: Russian Prime Minister Tests Positive for Coronavirus
item.description: Russian Prime Minister Mikhail Mishustin has tested positive for the new coronavirus, becoming the most recent world leader to contract the disease.

item.title: One Dead, Five Missing After Canadian Helicopter on NATO Mission Crashes Off Greece
item.description: One member of Canadaâ€™s navy is dead and five other service members are missing after a helicopter that was on a North Atlantic Treaty Organization training mission crashed off the coast of Greece.

item.title: Record Contraction in Eurozone Bodes Ill for Global Economy
item.description: The huge first-quarter decline in Europe portends deep pain and wide economic divergences in 2020.

item.title: U.S. Charges Honduran President's Police Ally in Drug Ring
item.description: Prosecutors and the Drug Enforcement Agency alleged that Juan Carlos Bonilla Valladares used his position to protect politically connected drug traffickers, facilitating multiton shipments of cocaine to the U.S.

item.title: U.S. Intelligence Agencies Confirm Investigating if Virus Emerged From Lab Accident
item.description: The U.S. intelligence community publicly confirmed that it is trying to determine whether the coronavirus that has caused a global pandemic may have escaped from a laboratory in Wuhan, the city where the crisis originated.

item.title: Workers Likely to Fare Better in Nations With Coronavirus Job-Retention Programs
item.description: Workers in Germany and Japan are likely to weather an expected coronavirus-induced global recession better than their U.S. peers, thanks in part to stronger job-retention programs, recent data suggest.
